# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: linode-akamai
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] The company was named after *akamai*, which means 'clever', or more colloquially 'cool', in Hawaiian.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Lewin found the term in a Hawaiian–English dictionary after a colleague's suggestion.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Akamai Technologies entered the 1998 MIT $50K competition (equivalent to $100K in 2025) with a business proposition based on their research on consistent hashing and was selected as one of the finalists.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] By August 1998, they had developed a working prototype, and with the help of Jonathan Seelig and Randall Kaplan, they took steps to incorporate the company.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Akamai Technologies was incorporated on August 20, 1998.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Conrades became chief executive officer of Akamai in April 1999.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] The company launched its commercial service in April 1999 and was listed on the NASDAQ Stock Market from October 29, 1999.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] On July 1, 2001, Akamai was added to the Russell 3000 Index and Russell 2000 Index.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] On September 11, 2001, co-founder Daniel M.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Lewin died in the September 11 attacks at the age of 31, when he was stabbed by one of the hijackers aboard American Airlines Flight 11, the first plane to crash into the World Trade Center.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] He was seated closest to the hijackers and may have tried to stop them.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Arabic news network Al Jazeera was an Akamai customer from March 28, 2003 to April 2, 2003, when Akamai decided to end the relationship, which the network's English-language managing editor claimed was due to "political pressure".
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] In 2005, Paul Sagan was named chief executive officer of Akamai, taking over from Conrades.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Sagan worked to differentiate Akamai from its competitors by expanding its breadth of services.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Under his leadership, it grew to $1.37 billion in revenue.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] In July 2007, Akamai was added to the S&P 500 index.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] In 2013, co-founder Tom Leighton was elected chief executive officer, replacing Sagan.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] In 2014 it was reported that the National Security Agency and Federal Bureau of Investigation used Facebook's Akamai CDN to collect information on Facebook users.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] On February 9, 2021, Akamai announced that it would reorganize into two internal groups – Security Technology and Edge Technology.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] It also re-established the role of chief technology officer and named Robert Blumofe to that role.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Long-time chief security officer (CSO) Andy Ellis announced he would leave in March 2021.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Akamai's headquarters are in Kendall Square.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] It started in Technology Square and later expanded to multiple buildings in Cambridge Center.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] It consolidated its offices in a purpose-built building at 145 Broadway in December 2019.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] The company's cloud infrastructure services primarily consist of compute and storage solutions developed based on Linode, a cloud hosting provider acquired by Akamai for $900 million in 2022.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] The Akamai Intelligent Platform is a distributed cloud computing platform that operates worldwide, a network of over approximately 365,000 servers in more than 135 countries.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] These servers reside on roughly 1,350 of the world's networks, gathering real-time information about traffic, congestion, and trouble spots.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Each Akamai server is equipped with proprietary software that uses complex algorithms to process requests from nearby users.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] The content delivery process begins with a user submitting a request to a browser.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] When a user enters a URL, a DNS request is triggered to Akamai's authoritative DNS, and an IP address is retrieved.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] With the IP address, the browser can then directly contact the Akamai edge server for subsequent requests.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] In a content delivery network (CDN) structure, the domain name of the URL is translated by the mapping system into the IP address of an edge server to serve the content to the user.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Akamai delivers web content over its Intelligent Platform by transparently mirroring elements such as HTML, CSS, software downloads, and media objects from customers' servers.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] The Akamai server is automatically chosen depending on the type of content and the user's network location.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] The servers are located in more than 200 countries and territories.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Receiving content from a server nearer to the user allows for faster downloads and less vulnerability to network congestion.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Akamai claims to provide better scalability by delivering the content over the last mile from servers close to end-users, avoiding the middle-mile bottleneck of the Internet.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] The Download Delivery product line includes HTTP downloads for large downloadable objects, a customizable application for consumers, and analytics tools with metrics that monitor and report on the download process.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] In addition to using its own servers, Akamai delivers certain content from other end-users' computers, in the form of peer-to-peer networking.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] On October 9, 2013, Akamai announced its Open Initiative at the 2013 Akamai Edge Conference.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] OPEN allows customers and partners to develop and customize how they interact with the Akamai Intelligent Platform.
[src:linode-akamai/akamai-technologies] Its key components include system and development operations integration, real-time big data integration, and a single-point user interface.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] In computing, **bandwidth** is the maximum rate of data transfer across a given path.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] Bandwidth may be characterized as **network bandwidth**, **data bandwidth**, or **digital bandwidth**.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The actual bit rate that can be achieved depends not only on the signal bandwidth but also on the noise on the channel.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The term *bandwidth* sometimes refers to the net bit rate, *peak bit rate*, *information rate*, physical-layer *useful bit rate*, channel capacity, or maximum throughput of a logical or physical communication path in a digital communication system.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] For example, bandwidth tests measure the maximum throughput of a computer network.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The maximum rate that can be sustained on a link is limited by the Shannon–Hartley channel capacity for these communication systems, which is dependent on the bandwidth in hertz and the noise on the channel.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The *consumed bandwidth* in bit/s corresponds to achieved throughput or goodput, i.e., the average rate of successful data transfer through a communication path.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The consumed bandwidth can be affected by technologies such as bandwidth shaping, bandwidth management, bandwidth throttling, bandwidth cap, bandwidth allocation (for example bandwidth allocation protocol and dynamic bandwidth allocation), etc.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] A bit stream's bandwidth is proportional to the average consumed signal bandwidth in hertz (the average spectral bandwidth of the analog signal representing the bit stream) during a studied time interval.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The asymptotic bandwidth (formally *asymptotic throughput*) for a network is the measure of maximum throughput for a greedy source, for example when the message size (the number of packets per second from a source) approaches close to the maximum amount.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] Asymptotic bandwidths are usually estimated by sending a number of very large messages through the network, measuring the end-to-end throughput.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] As with other bandwidths, the asymptotic bandwidth is measured in multiples of bits per seconds.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] Since bandwidth spikes can skew the measurement, carriers often use the 95th percentile method.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] This method continuously measures bandwidth usage and then removes the top 5 percent.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] Digital bandwidth may also refer to: multimedia bit rate or average bitrate after multimedia data compression (source coding), defined as the total amount of data divided by the playback time.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] Due to the impractically high bandwidth requirements of uncompressed digital media, the required multimedia bandwidth can be significantly reduced with data compression.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The most widely used data compression technique for media bandwidth reduction is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which was first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in the early 1970s.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] DCT compression significantly reduces the amount of memory and bandwidth required for digital signals, capable of achieving a data compression ratio of up to 100:1 compared to uncompressed media.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] In web hosting service, the term *bandwidth* is often used to describe the amount of data transferred to or from the website or server within a prescribed period of time, for example *bandwidth consumption accumulated over a month* measured in gigabytes per month.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The more accurate phrase used for this meaning of a maximum amount of data transfer each month or given period is *monthly data transfer*.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] A similar situation can occur for end-user Internet service providers as well, especially where network capacity is limited (for example in areas with underdeveloped internet connectivity and on wireless networks).
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] Edholm's law, proposed by and named after Phil Edholm in 2004, holds that the bandwidth of telecommunication networks double every 18 months, which has proven to be true since the 1970s.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The trend is evident in the cases of Internet, cellular (mobile), wireless LAN and wireless personal area networks.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The MOSFET (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor) is the most important factor enabling the rapid increase in bandwidth.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] The MOSFET (MOS transistor) was invented by Mohamed M.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] Atalla and Dawon Kahng at Bell Labs in 1959, and went on to become the basic building block of modern telecommunications technology.
[src:linode-akamai/bandwidth-computing] Continuous MOSFET scaling, along with various advances in MOS technology, has enabled both Moore's law (transistor counts in integrated circuit chips doubling every two years) and Edholm's law (communication bandwidth doubling every 18 months).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A **data center** is a facility used to house computer systems and associated components, such as telecommunications and storage systems.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data centers are critical infrastructure for the storage and processing of information, and they support the global financial system, cloud services, machine learning, and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data centers vary widely in terms of size, power and water requirements, and overall structure.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Hyperscale and colocation facilities collectively account for approximately 74% of U.S. server energy consumption as of 2023, a share that has grown significantly over the past decade as workloads have migrated away from enterprise on-premises infrastructure.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Since IT operations are crucial for business continuity, a data center generally includes redundant or backup components.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Other important design considerations are power supply, network infrastructure, environmental controls (e.g., cooling, fire suppression), and various measures for physical and data security.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Large data centers operate at an industrial scale, requiring significant energy.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Estimated global data center electricity consumption in 2024 was around 415 terawatt hours (TWh), or about 1.5% of global electricity demand.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The International Energy Agency (IEA) projects that data center electricity consumption could double by 2030.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of data center infrastructure has prompted regulatory debates in multiple jurisdictions regarding tax incentives, electricity grid impacts, water consumption, and compatibility with state and national climate commitments.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Rapid growth of the AI industry is leading to strain on electric grids and increased electricity costs for consumers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] This in turn has drawn growing opposition to new data centers from local people who would bear the burdens of social and environmental impacts, such as energy and water use, while faraway actors and institutions would receive the projects' benefits.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] These opposition movements have materialized especially in parts of Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Billions of dollars in projects were halted or delayed by data center resistances in the U.S. between May 2024 and June 2025.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data centers are usually classified according to their ownership model, scale, and intended use.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] However, these classifications are not mutually exclusive from each other, and they may overlap depending on the operational structure and service model of the particular data center.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Enterprise data centers are owned and operated by a single organization for their own internal information technology (IT) needs, rather than for commercial hosting of other companies' data.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] They used to be essential infrastructures; as in 2014, enterprise data centers accounted for over 60% of the U.S. server energy consumption, but this share fell sharply to about 10% by 2023 as workloads migrated to hyperscale and colocation facilities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Energy efficiency at an enterprise data center tends to be significantly lower than at hyperscale facilities due to its cooling, which can account for over 30% of electricity consumption at enterprise sites, compared to roughly 7% at efficient hyperscale data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The shift away from enterprise facilities toward cloud and colocation infrastructure is one of the defining structural trends of the previous decade.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Colocation centers provide shared physical infrastructure, such as power, cooling, space, etc., to multiple tenants who lease space rather than building their own facilities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Colocation data centers reduce expenditure for organizations while enabling operators to achieve economies of scale in power procurement and cooling efficiency.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Some of the largest data centers in the world are colocation centers, and this category accounted for about 22% of worldwide data center capacity as of 2024, making them the second-largest category by capacity after hyperscale facilities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Major colocation providers include Equinix, Switch, COPT, and Digital Realty, which operate facilities across multiple continents.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Hyperscale data centers are large-scale facilities, typically exceeding 100 megawatts of power capacity, designed to support massive, scalable computing workloads for cloud services, AI training, and large-scale data processing.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] By the end of 2024, there were 1,136 operational hyperscale data centers globally, a figure that doubled over the previous five years, with the U.S. accounting for approximately 54% of total hyperscale capacity.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In particular, the three largest operators, Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud, collectively account for approximately 59% of all hyperscale data center capacity globally.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] As a growing trend, hyperscale data centers represented about 41% of worldwide data center capacity in 2024 and are projected to exceed 60% by 2029 as enterprise on-premises infrastructure continues to decline.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Moreover, as artificial intelligence (AI) is becoming widely used, AI data centers are being built more rapidly, and they can consume as much electricity as 100,000 households, more than conventional data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Since 2024, there has been widespread grassroots Opposition to AI Data Centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Edge data centers are smaller facilities, typically ranging from 1 to 10 megawatts.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] They are positioned closer to end users or data sources to reduce network latency and support real-time applications, such as autonomous vehicles, industrial automation, and content delivery.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Unlike hyperscale data centers, edge data centers are intentionally distributed across many locations rather than consolidated, with deployments occurring in urban areas, cell tower sites, as well as industrial locations.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The growth of edge computing infrastructure has been tied to the expansion of 5G wireless networks and the increasing use of Internet of Things (IoT) devices, which generate data that is more efficiently processed near its source than transmitted to a centralized data center.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Micro data centers (MDCs) are access-level data centers that are smaller in size than traditional data centers but provide the same features.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] They are typically located near the data source to reduce communication delays, as their small size allows several MDCs to be spread out over a wide area.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] MDCs are suited to user-facing, front end applications.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] They are commonly used in edge computing and other areas where low latency data processing is needed.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Modularity and flexibility are key elements in allowing a data center to grow and change over time.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data center modules are pre-engineered, standardized building blocks that can be configured and moved as needed.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A modular data center may consist of data center equipment contained within shipping containers or similar portable containers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Components of the data center can be prefabricated and standardized, which facilitates moving if needed.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] These modular data centers are useful for IT disaster recovery.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Mobile data centers are also used to move large quantities of data, by physically transporting the hardware that contains it, and in cryptocurrency mining, where fleets of mobile data centers are transported to take advantage of cheaper sources of energy.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data centers have their roots in the huge computer rooms of the 1940s, typified by the Electronic Numerical Integrator and Computer (ENIAC), one of the earliest examples of a data center.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Early computer systems were complex to operate and maintain, and required a special environment in which to operate.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Many cables were necessary to connect all of the components, and methods to accommodate and organize these were devised such as standard racks to mount equipment, raised floors, and cable trays (installed overhead or under the elevated floor).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A single mainframe required a great deal of power and had to be cooled to avoid overheating.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Security became important – computers were expensive, and were often used for government and military purposes.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] As such, basic design guidelines for controlling access to the computer room were devised.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] During the microcomputer industry boom of the 1980s, computers started to be deployed everywhere, in many cases with little or no care about operating requirements.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] However, as information technology (IT) operations started to grow in complexity, organizations grew aware of the need to control IT resources.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The availability of inexpensive networking equipment, coupled with new standards for the network structured cabling, made it possible to use a hierarchical design that put servers in a specific room inside the company.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The use of the term *data center*, as applied to specially designed computer rooms, started to gain popular recognition about this time.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] During the dot-com bubble (1997–2000), there was a boom in data center construction because companies needed fast Internet connectivity and non-stop operation to establish their Internet presence.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The global data center market saw steady growth in the 2010s, with a notable acceleration in the latter half of the decade.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] According to Gartner, worldwide data center infrastructure spending reached $200 billion in 2021, representing a 6% increase from 2020 despite economic challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2024, global energy consumption from data centers was 620 TWh, with 80% of that consumption concentrated in the U.S., China, and the United Kingdom.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Colocation centers were the most common category worldwide, with 4,799 colocation centers in 127 countries.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In that year, the largest data center in the world was Citadel, owned by Switch, at the Tahoe Reno Industrial Center in Reno, Nevada, occupying 7.2 million square feet.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Growth of the data center industry has prompted local resistance.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A 2023 survey found social mobilizations against the industry in Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] These movements expressed concern about the centers' energy and water use, pollution, and impact on agriculture or the landscape.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A 2026 poll by *Politico* suggested that resistance to growth of the industry would make candidates' stance on data centers a significant issue for voters in the U.S.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The U.S. hosted 5,381 data centers in March 2024, the highest number of any country worldwide, accounting for 40% of the global market in 2023.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] As of 2023, about 80% of U.S. data center load was concentrated in 15 states, led by Virginia and Texas.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] As of 2025, roughly one third of America's data centers were in three states: Virginia (643), Texas (395), and California (319).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The largest concentration of data centers in the world is in Northern Virginia, with over 250 facilities in the region.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2025, Georgia was the fastest growing data center hub in the U.S., having enacted several state tax exemptions for the industry and hosting between 100 and 150 centers in the state.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Local governments have responded to the growing industry in Georgia with a variety of local ordinances to guide permitting of these facilities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The consultancy firm McKinsey & Co., projected U.S. demand to double to 35 gigawatts (GW) by 2030, up from 17 GW in 2022.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A study published by the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) in May 2024 estimated that data centers could consume between 4.6% and 9.1% of the country's electricity generation by 2030.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] GDP growth was only 0.1% without the investments in data centers for artificial intelligence.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data centers house critical computing resources in a controlled environment and must generally operate with very high availability.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Key design elements include providing power for the equipment, temperature and humidity control, cabling, fire safety, and security.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] For this reason, a data center has to offer a secure environment that minimizes the chances of a security breach.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Industry research company International Data Corporation (IDC) puts the average age of a data center at nine years old.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Gartner, another research company, says data centers older than seven years are obsolete.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The growth in data (163 zettabytes by 2025) is one factor driving the need for data centers to modernize.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Rapid obsolescence of data center equipment was a concern by at least 2007, and in 2011, Uptime Institute was concerned about aging equipment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The topology proposed in this document is intended to be applicable to any size data center.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Telcordia GR-3160, *NEBS Requirements for Telecommunications Data Center Equipment and Spaces*, provides guidelines for data center spaces within telecommunications networks, and environmental requirements for the equipment intended for installation in those spaces.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] These criteria were developed jointly by Telcordia and industry representatives.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] They may be applied to data center spaces housing data processing or IT equipment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Power supplies, either back up or continuous onsite power, consist of one or more uninterruptible power supplies, battery banks, diesel, gas turbine, and/or gas engine generating sets.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Greater primary fuel energy efficiency can be achieved with the use of cogeneration technology, generating electricity, heating, and cooling onsite.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] To prevent single points of failure, all elements of the electrical systems, including backup systems, are typically given redundant copies, and critical servers are connected to both the *A-side* and *B-side* power feeds.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] This arrangement is often made to achieve N+1 redundancy in the systems.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Static transfer switches are sometimes used to ensure instantaneous switchover from one supply to the other in the event of a power failure.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Options for low-voltage cable routing might include data cabling that is routed through overhead cable trays; raised floor cabling, both for security reasons and to avoid the extra cost of cooling systems over the racks; and anti-static tiles for flooring, especially in low-cost data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Maintaining suitable temperature and humidity levels is critical to preventing equipment damage caused by overheating.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Overheating can cause components (usually the silicon or copper of the wires or circuits) to melt, causing loose connections and fire hazards.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Typical temperature control methods include air conditioning and indirect cooling, such as the use of outside air, indirect evaporative cooling units, and seawater cooling.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Airflow management is the practice of achieving data center cooling efficiency by preventing the recirculation of hot exhaust air and by reducing bypass airflow.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Common approaches include hot-aisle/cold-aisle containment and the deployment of in-row cooling units, which position cooling directly between server racks to intercept exhaust heat before it mixes with room air.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Humidity control prevents moisture and related issues.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] For example, excess humidity can cause dust to adhere more readily to fan blades and heat sinks, impeding air cooling and leading to higher temperatures.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Cold aisle containment is done by exposing the rear of equipment racks, while the fronts of the servers are enclosed with doors and covers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] This is similar to how large-scale food companies refrigerate and store products.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Computer cabinets/server farms are often organized for containment of hot/cold aisles.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Proper air duct placement prevents cold and hot air from mixing.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Rows of cabinets are paired to face each other so the cool and hot air intakes and exhausts do not mix air, which would severely reduce cooling efficiency.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Alternatively, a range of underfloor panels can create efficient cold air pathways directed to the raised-floor vented tiles.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Either the cold aisle or the hot aisle can be contained.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Another option is fitting cabinets with vertical exhaust duct chimneys.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Hot exhaust pipes/vents/ducts can direct the air into a plenum space above a dropped ceiling and back to the cooling units or to outside vents.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] With this configuration, traditional hot/cold aisle configuration is not required.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data centers feature fire protection systems, including passive and active design elements, as well as implementation of fire prevention programs in operations.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Smoke detectors are usually installed to provide early warning of a fire.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Although the main room usually does not allow wet pipe-based systems due to the fragile nature of circuit boards, there are systems that can be used in the rest of the facility or in cold/hot aisle air circulation systems that are closed systems.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] These include sprinkler systems and misting, the latter of which uses high pressure to create extremely small water droplets and can be used in sensitive rooms due to the nature of the droplets.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] However, there are other means to put out fires, especially in Sensitive areas, usually using gaseous fire suppression, of which Halon gas was the most popular, until the negative effects of producing and using it were discovered.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Physical access to data centers is usually restricted.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Layered security often starts with fencing, bollards, and mantraps.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Video camera surveillance and permanent security guards are almost always present if the data center is large or contains sensitive information.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Fingerprint recognition is starting to become commonplace.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Logging access is required by some data protection regulations; some organizations tightly link this to access control systems.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Multiple log entries can occur at the main entrance, entrances to internal rooms, and at equipment cabinets.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Access control at cabinets can be integrated with intelligent power distribution units, so locks are networked through the same appliance.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data center transformation takes a step-by-step approach through integrated projects carried out over time.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] This differs from a traditional method of data center upgrades, which takes a serial and siloed approach.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Typical projects within a data center transformation initiative include standardization/consolidation, virtualization, automation, and security.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data center consolidation consists of reducing the number of data centers and avoiding *server sprawl* (both physical and virtual), which often includes replacing aging data center equipment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] This process is aided by standardization, which makes these systems follow a uniform set of configurations to simplify and improve efficiency.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Automating tasks such as provisioning, configuration, patching, release management, and compliance are other ways in which data centers can be upgraded.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] These changes are needed not just when facing fewer skilled IT workers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Lastly, security initiatives integrate the protection of virtual systems with existing security for physical infrastructures.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The first raised floor computer room was made by IBM in 1956 to allow access for wiring.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] During the 1970s, raised floors became more common because they allow cool air to circulate more efficiently.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A raised floor standards guide (GR-2930) was developed by Telcordia Technologies, a subsidiary of Ericsson.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The "lights-out" data center, also known as a darkened or dark data center, is a data center that has largely eliminated the need for direct access by personnel, except under extraordinary circumstances.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Due to the lack of need for staff to enter the data center, it can be operated without lighting.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] All of the devices are accessed and managed by remote systems, with automation programs used to perform unattended operations.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In addition to the energy savings, reduction in staffing costs, and the ability to locate the site further from population centers, implementing a lights-out data center also reduces the threat of malicious attacks upon the infrastructure.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) regulations require monitoring of noise levels inside data centers if noise exceeds 85 decibels.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The average noise level in server areas of a data center may reach as high as 92–96 dB(A).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Residents living near data centers have described the sound as "a high-pitched whirring noise 24/7", saying "It's like being on a tarmac with an airplane engine running constantly ...
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] External sources of noise include HVAC (heating, ventilation, and air conditioning) equipment and energy generators.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Location factors include proximity to power grids, telecommunications infrastructure, networking services, transportation lines, and emergency services.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Other considerations should include flight paths, neighboring power drains, geological risks, and climate (associated with cooling costs).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Local political considerations, such as availability of subsidies and lack of opposition, are also important factors in locating data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Various metrics exist to measure the data-availability that results from data-center availability beyond 95% uptime, with the top of the scale counting how many *nines* can be placed after *99%*.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The costs of avoiding downtime should not exceed the cost of the downtime itself.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Dynamic infrastructure provides the ability to intelligently, automatically, and securely move workloads within a data center anytime, anywhere, for migrations, provisioning, to enhance performance, or build co-location facilities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] It also facilitates performing routine maintenance on either physical or virtual systems, all while minimizing interruption.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A related concept is Composable Infrastructure, which allows for the dynamic reconfiguration of the available resources to suit needs, only when needed.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Communications in modern data centers are most often based on networks running the Internet protocol suite.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data centers contain a set of routers and switches that transport traffic between the servers and to the outside world, which are connected according to the data center network architecture.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Redundancy of the internet connection is often provided by using two or more upstream service providers (see Multihoming).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Some of the servers at a data center are used for running the basic internet and intranet services needed by internal users in the organization, e.g., e-mail servers, proxy servers, and DNS servers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Network security elements are also usually deployed: firewalls, VPN gateways, intrusion detection systems, and so on.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Also common are monitoring systems for the network and some of the applications.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Additional off-site monitoring systems are also typical, in case of a failure of communications inside the data center.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Energy consumption and the environmental impacts it creates are a central issue for data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Power draw ranges from a few kilowatts (kW) for small server racks to several tens of megawatts (MW) for large facilities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Modern hyperscale data centers can exhibit power densities exceeding 100 times those of conventional office buildings, primarily due to the high concentration of servers and cooling systems required to manage continuous digital workloads.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] For higher power density facilities, electricity costs are a dominant operating expense and account for over 10% of the total cost of ownership (TCO) of a data center.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] As of 2024, data centers in the U.S. are primarily powered by natural gas, which supplies 40% of their electricity (with renewable energy at 24%, nuclear at about 20%, and coal at about 15%).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The *Associated Press* reported that electricity for AI data centers in the U.S. would likely come from natural gas or oil, as companies prefer using currently available power plants, which primarily use fossil fuels.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Fossil energy is also often cheaper in locations where data centers are developed, and experts believe that energy demands from generative AI and data centers would be difficult to fulfill with renewable energy alone.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Some companies such as Google, Amazon, and Meta have expressed interest in nuclear power for their data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] As of 2020, according to the IEA, solar photovoltaic-generated electricity is at its lowest cost in history.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Other data centers, including xAI's Colossus, OpenAI's Stargate, and Meta's Prometheus use their own off-grid natural gas plants.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Electric vehicle and lithium-ion batteries have also been used for powering data centers, including for Colossus.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Power utility companies make upgrades to their infrastructure to handle demands of new data centers, and the price for these changes typically falls on residential or smaller commercial consumers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2025, the Mountain Valley Pipeline announced plans to expand its capacity by 25% to meet energy needs for data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In December 2025, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) published a unanimous order allowing data centers in the U.S. to have a direct connection with power plants.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] United States Secretary of Energy Chris Wright expressed support for un-retiring coal plants to power AI data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Electricity demands from AI data centers have slowed or reversed the retirement of peaking power plants in the U.S.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] For example, in 2025, Southern Company announced that energy use from data centers would prevent the company from retiring coal-fired power plants as it had earlier promised.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In Nevada, the Desert Research Institute (DRI) calculated that 35% of the state's energy production could go to data centers by the year 2030 if all projects planned in the state as of 2026 are completed.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] DRI also stated, in areas where there are clusters of data centers, local consumers may end up paying the extra cost of expanding infrastructure.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2024, data centers were estimated to account for about 1.5% of global electricity consumption (approximately 415 TWh) and around 1% of greenhouse gas emissions according to U.S.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] However, the rapid expansion is causing projections to rise sharply.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Due to accelerated demand from AI, data center's global electricity consumption is projected to more than double to around 945 TWh by 2030 in the IEA's base-case scenario, which represents just under 3% of 2030 total global electricity consumption.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] This growing electricity demand, much of which is still generated by fossil fuels, increases the potential environmental impacts.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In addition to operational energy demand, embodied life cycle emissions should be considered, which include the extraction, manufacturing, transportation, and recycling or disposal of materials used in the construction of facilities and hardware.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Global data center carbon dioxide emissions are projected to rise from an estimated 220 million tonnes in 2024 to 300–320 million tonnes by 2035.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google and Microsoft each consumed more power than over 100 countries.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] As a result, there is increasing industry pressure for decarbonization.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Companies are pursuing direct clean energy agreements, such as Tencent who has pledged to be carbon neutral by 2030, and Microsoft's 2024 agreement to re-open the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant to provide 100% of the electric power for its AI data centers for 20 years.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The most commonly used energy efficiency metric for data centers is power usage effectiveness (PUE), calculated as the ratio of total power entering the data center divided by the power used by IT equipment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] PUE measures the percentage of power used by overhead devices (cooling, lighting, etc.).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The average U.S. data center has a PUE of 2.0, meaning two watts of total power (overhead + IT equipment) for every watt delivered to IT equipment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] State-of-the-art data centers are estimated to have a PUE of roughly 1.2.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Google publishes quarterly efficiency metrics from its data centers in operation.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] PUEs of as low as 1.01 have been achieved with two-phase immersion cooling.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The EPA has an Energy Star rating for standalone or large data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] To qualify for the ecolabel, a data center must be within the top quartile in energy efficiency of all reported facilities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The Energy Efficiency Improvement Act of 2015 (U.S.) requires federal facilities—including data centers—to operate more efficiently.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] California's Title 24 (2014) of the California Code of Regulations mandates that every newly constructed data center must have some form of airflow containment in place to optimize energy efficiency.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The European Union (EU) also has a similar initiative: EU Code of Conduct for Data Centres.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Efficiency improvements and renewable energy integration are helping offset some emissions, but fossil fuels remain a major electricity source for data center operations worldwide.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2011, server racks in data centers were designed for more than 25 kW, and the typical server was estimated to waste about 30% of the electricity it consumed.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The energy demand for information storage systems is also rising.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A high-availability data center is estimated to have a 1 MW demand and consume $20 million in electricity over its lifetime, with cooling representing 35% to 45% of the data center's total cost of ownership.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Calculations show that in two years, the cost of powering and cooling a server could be equal to the cost of purchasing the server hardware.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Research in 2018 showed that a substantial amount of energy could still be conserved by optimizing IT refresh rates and increasing server use.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Research for optimizing task scheduling is also underway, with researchers looking to implement energy-efficient scheduling algorithms that could reduce energy consumption by anywhere between 6% and 44%.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2011, Facebook, Rackspace, and others founded the Open Compute Project (OCP) to develop and publish open standards for greener data center computing technologies.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] As part of the project, Facebook published the designs of its server, which it had built for its first dedicated data center in Prineville.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Making servers taller left space for more effective heat sinks and enabled the use of fans that moved more air with less energy.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] By not buying commercial off-the-shelf servers, energy consumption due to unnecessary expansion slots on the motherboard and unneeded components, such as a graphics card, was also saved.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2016, Google joined the project and published the designs of its 48V DC shallow data center rack.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] This design had long been part of Google data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] By eliminating the multiple transformers usually deployed in data centers, Google had achieved a 30% increase in energy efficiency.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2017, sales for data center hardware built to OCP designs topped $1.2 billion and are expected to reach $6 billion by 2021.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Power is the largest recurring cost to the user of a data center.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2008, the ASHRAE recommended a temperature range of 64.4 °F (18.0 °C) to 80.6 °F (27.0 °C), though some data centers could operate at higher temperatures.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] However, cooling at or below 70 °F (21 °C) wastes money and energy.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Furthermore, overcooling equipment in environments with a high relative humidity can expose equipment to a high amount of moisture that facilitates the growth of salt deposits on conductive filaments in the circuitry.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A **power and cooling analysis**, also referred to as a thermal assessment, measures the relative temperatures in specific areas as well as the capacity of the cooling systems to handle specific ambient temperatures.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Power cooling density is a measure of how much square footage the center can cool at maximum capacity.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The cooling of data centers is the second largest power consumer after servers, with cooling taking about 7% to 30% of energy usage (depending on efficiency), compared to an average of 60% of energy used by servers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] An energy efficiency analysis measures the energy use of data center IT and facilities equipment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A typical energy efficiency analysis measures factors such as a data center's Power Use Effectiveness (PUE) against industry standards, identifies mechanical and electrical sources of inefficiency, and identifies air-management metrics.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] However, the limitation of most current metrics and approaches is they do not include IT in the analysis.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Case studies have shown that by addressing energy efficiency holistically in a data center, major efficiencies can be achieved that are not possible otherwise.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Thermal zone mapping uses sensors and computer modeling to create a three-dimensional image of the hot and cool zones in a data center.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] This information can help identify optimal positioning of data center equipment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] For example, critical servers might be placed in a cool zone that is serviced by redundant AC units.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Data centers use a lot of power, consumed via two main usages: the power required to run the equipment and the power required to cool the equipment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Power efficiency reduces the first category.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Cooling cost reduction through natural means includes location decisions.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] When the focus is avoiding good fiber connectivity, power grid connections, and people concentrations to manage the equipment, a data center can be miles away from users.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Mass data centers like Google or Facebook do not need to be near population centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Arctic locations that can use outside air, which provides cooling, are becoming more popular.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Countries with favorable conditions, such as Canada, Finland, Sweden, Norway, and Switzerland are trying to attract cloud computing data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Singapore lifted a three-year ban on new data centers in April 2022.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A major data center hub for the Asia-Pacific region, Singapore lifted its moratorium on new data center projects in 2022, granting four new projects, but rejecting more than 16 data center applications from over 20 received.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] It is very difficult to reuse the heat that comes from air-cooled data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] For this reason, data center infrastructures are more often equipped with heat pumps.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of artificial intelligence (AI) and high-performance computing workloads has increased attention on data center power infrastructure, particularly the relationship between electrical reliability, deployment timelines, energy costs, and decarbonization objectives.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Industry publications have described phased approaches to infrastructure development that enable operators to deploy power capacity rapidly while maintaining pathways toward lower-carbon energy systems as technologies, fuel availability, grid capacity, and economics evolve.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Recent industry discussion has also emphasized "speed-to-power" as a significant consideration in data center development, reflecting the growing importance of securing electrical capacity and resilient power systems within increasingly compressed project timelines.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In the 2020s, the rapid growth of data center construction gave rise to policy debates over tax incentives, electricity grid, water resources, and climate commitments.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] By 2024, at least 36 U.S. states had introduced specific tax incentives aimed at attracting data center investment, most often in the form of sales tax exemptions on servers, networking equipment, and electricity.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Virginia hosts the largest concentration of data centers in the U.S., and a December 2024 audit by its Joint Legislative Audit and Review Commission (JLARC) put the industry's annual contribution at roughly 74,000 jobs and $9.1 billion in gross state product.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The audit reported that the state's sales and use tax exemption was claimed by about 90% of operators and that reduced state revenue by an estimated $928 million in fiscal year 2023.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Thus, JLARC concluded that ending the exemption would likely shrink Virginia's share of new data center investment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Economists have debated the effectiveness of such incentives more broadly.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Further, research by Timothy Bartik of the Upjohn Institute estimated that economic development incentives change firm location decisions in only 2% to 25% of cases.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In response to tax exemption policies, several jurisdictions have started to reevaluate incentives for data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2024, the Georgia General Assembly passed legislation to terminate the state's data center sales tax exemption.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] However, the bill was ultimately vetoed by Governor Brian Kemp.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In another case in 2026, the Virginia Senate voted 28 to 12 to phase out the state's data center sales tax exemption as part of broader budget negotiations.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Most large data centers use water for evaporative cooling of their servers, and the volumes involved have drawn growing scrutiny.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A 2021 study in *npj Clean Water* estimated that U.S. data centers directly consume about 1.7 billion liters of water per day, with up to 57% of that drawn from potable supplies, and noted that fewer than one-third of operators measured their water use at the time.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] A separate study published in *Environmental Research Letters* found that about one-fifth of direct water use by U.S. data centers came from moderately or highly water-stressed watersheds, and that nearly half of the country's servers ran on electricity drawn from water-stressed regions.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] According to a 2024 Berkeley Lab report, data centers in the U.S. had used approximately 17 billion gallons of water.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The same report expected hyperscale data centers specifically to use 16 to 33 billion gallons of water per year by 2028.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In Virginia, the December 2024 JLARC audit reported that data centers in the state consumed about 2.1 billion gallons of water in 2023, an 86% increase since 2019, and that roughly one-third of that came from reclaimed water rather than potable supplies.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The audit recommended that local governments be authorized to require water-use estimates as part of the data center permitting process.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] There is no federal U.S. standard requiring data center operators to disclose water consumption, and access to facility-level data has often been limited by non-disclosure agreements (NDAs) with host municipalities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2022, the city of The Dalles, Oregon, settled a public records lawsuit brought by *The Oregonian*, after which Google ended its nationwide practice of treating site-level water use as a trade secret.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2025, several states considered legislation to require data centers to disclose water use, including bills in Virginia, California, and New Jersey, although each was vetoed by the state's governor that year.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The growth of data center electricity demand in the 2020s has prompted regulatory debates over grid capacity, transmission planning, and how the costs of new infrastructure should be allocated among customers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The 2024 Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL) report on U.S. data center energy use, prepared at the request of the U.S.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Congress, estimated that data centers accounted for about 4.4% of national electricity consumption in 2023 and projected a rise to between 6.7% and 12% by 2028, depending on growth scenarios.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2025, the IEA projected that data centers would account for nearly half of new U.S. electricity demand growth through 2030.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), the federally designated electric reliability organization for the U.S., identified data centers as the single largest driver of projected demand growth in its 2024 long-term reliability assessment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Additionally, NERC documented a voltage event in the PJM Interconnection region in July 2024, in which roughly 1,500 megawatts of data center load disconnected simultaneously across about 60 facilities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] How the costs of meeting this demand are shared has also become a central policy question.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The JLARC audit in 2024 estimated that, without any changes to how rates are designed, typical residential customers of Dominion Energy Virginia could see their bills rise by $14 to $37 per month by 2040 because of data center-driven grid investment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] As such, the report recommended creating a separate customer rate class for large data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Some researchers have urged caution in interpreting demand projections.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Furthermore, a 2024 commentary in the journal *Joule* argued that public estimates of future data center electricity use vary widely and that utilities have historically over-forecasted load growth, and called for more transparent data on actual facility-level consumption.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The growth of data centers has raised questions about whether the renewable energy commitments made by their operators are consistent with broader climate goals.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Many large operators report meeting electricity-related emissions targets through annual purchases of renewable energy certificates (RECs) or matching their total annual consumption with renewable generation.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2022, a study by *Nature Climate Change* analyzed 115 companies with Science Based Targets.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] It found that about 42% of their reported Scope 2 emissions reductions disappeared once REC-based claims were excluded.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] This directly suggests that some corporate climate progress reflected accounting choices rather than actual reductions in grid emissions.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In response, some operators and researchers have proposed 24/7 carbon-free energy matching.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Under this approach, every hour of a facility's electricity use must be matched with carbon-free generation on the same regional grid.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The authors found that annual or volumetric matching did little to cut grid emissions under current U.S. policy.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Hourly 24/7 matching cut more, but it cost about $13 to $30 more per megawatt-hour.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] The tension between data center expansion and corporate climate goals has also become apparent in the operators' own disclosures of information.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google reported its greenhouse gas emissions had risen by about 48% since 2019, attributing the increase in large part to data center electricity use associated with AI workloads.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Similarly, Microsoft reported in 2024 that its emissions had risen by about 29% since 2020, citing the construction and operation of new data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p01] Moreover, the IEA projected in 2025 that global data center carbon dioxide emissions could peak at around 320 million tonnes by 2030 before declining slightly through 2035, with the trajectory depending heavily on the carbon intensity of the electricity supplied to new facilities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Data centers have significant impacts on local ecologies, politics, and utility infrastructure.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Political and economic incentives such as tax breaks, land deals, or government subsidies drive data center growth in areas where these incentives are available.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Data centers are frequently located in rural areas, where they may displace agriculture.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Growth in the data center industry has prompted several debates about environmental impacts, especially the massive energy and water demands.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] The supply chains, emissions, and e-waste also impose significant planetary impacts, raising questions of environmental injustice toward marginalized communities that frequently bear these burdens.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Multiple studies and experts have found that data centers do not bring high-paying jobs to local communities in proportion to the tax subsidies they receive.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] The rapid expansion of AI data centers has raised significant concerns over their water consumption, particularly in drought-prone regions.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] According to the IEA, a single 100-megawatt data center, using 2400 MWh of electricity per day, can use up to 2,000,000 litres (530,000 US gal) of water per day.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] The electricity use is equivalent to that of 60,000–120,000 households in the U.S., while water use is equivalent about 6,500 households.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Water usage can be divided into three categories: on-site (direct usage from data centers), off-site (indirect usage from electricity), and supply-chain (water usage from manufacturing processes).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] On-site water use refers to the direct water consumed by the data center for the cooling of its equipment.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Water is used specifically for space humidification (adding moisture to the air), evaporative cooling systems (cooling air before entering server rooms), and cooling towers (removing heat from the facility).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Off-site water use is the indirect water usage from the electricity generated in data centers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] It is estimated that 56% of U.S. data centers' electricity comes from fossil fuels in thermal power stations, which use water to generate power via steam.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Lastly, data centers consume water through the process of AI chip and server manufacturing.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] These chips, specifically, consume a vast amount of ultrapure water for fabrication and cooling of semiconductor plants.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] While this scope of water usage is not as significant as on-site and off-site water usage, it is still a contributing factor.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Globally, since 2022, more than two-thirds of new data centers have been built in water-stressed areas, including Texas, Arizona, Saudi Arabia, and India, where freshwater scarcity is already a critical issue.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] The global water footprint of data centers is estimated at 560 billion litres (150×10^9 US gal) annually, a figure projected to double by 2030 due to increasing AI demand.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] In regions like Aragon, Spain, Amazon's planned data centers are licensed to withdraw 755,720 cubic metres (612.67 acre⋅ft) of water per year, sparking conflicts with farmers who rely on the same dwindling supplies.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Similar tensions have arisen in Chile, the Netherlands, and Uruguay, where communities protest the diversion of water for tech infrastructure.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Tech companies, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon, have pledged to become "water positive" by 2030, aiming to replenish more water than they consume.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] However, critics argue that such commitments often rely on water offsetting, which does not address acute local shortages.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] At least 59 additional data centers are planned for water-stressed U.S. regions by 2028, and AI's global water demand is projected to reach 6.6 billion cubic metres (1,700×10^9 US gal) by 2027.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Data centers generate significant electronic waste (e-waste) due to the frequent replacement of hardware such as servers, GPUs, CPUs, memory, and storage devices, often every 2–5 years to meet demands for digital transformation and AI.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Globally, e-waste totaled 62 million metric tons in 2022, with generative AI projected to contribute 1.2 to 5 million metric tons annually by 2030, including valuable metals like copper and gold, and hazardous substances such as lead and mercury.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] In the U.S., data centers contribute to an annual loss of $10 billion in discarded e-waste value, including $4 billion in precious metals.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Only 22% of global e-waste is formally collected and recycled, exacerbating environmental pollution and health risks in informal processing sites, often in developing countries where exported waste is handled.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] From a political ecology perspective, data center e-waste highlights power imbalances in resource management and environmental justice, as tech corporations benefit from tax incentives while externalizing costs to marginalized communities through toxic exports and landfill burdens.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where shared resources like metals are depleted without equitable governance.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Mitigation strategies include modular hardware designs, secure data erasure for reuse, and extended producer responsibility policies to reduce waste by up to 86% in optimized scenarios.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] According to one 2025 energy model, the U.S. could see energy prices increase 8% nationally by 2030.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Higher electricity prices are already occurring in some regions, particularly those with lots of data centers like Santa Clara, California, and parts of upstate New York.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Data centers have also generated concerns in Northern Virginia about whether residents will have to foot the bill for future power lines.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] It has also made it harder to develop housing in London.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] A Bank of America Institute report in July 2024 found that increased demand for electricity due in part to AI has been pushing electricity prices higher and is a significant contributor to electricity inflation.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] A Harvard Law School report in March 2025 found that because utilities are increasingly in competition to attract data center contracts from big tech companies, they are likely hiding subsidies to those trillion-dollar companies in power prices by raising costs for American consumers.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Data centers have increasingly been analyzed through the lens of political ecology, which explores the intersections of power, politics, and environmental change in technological infrastructure.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Scholars argue that these facilities reshape urban and rural landscapes by existing in marginalized or post-industrial areas, often repurposing abandoned sites while promising economic revitalization through job creation and tax revenues.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] For instance, hyperscale data centers in rural towns like Prineville, Oregon, or Luleå, Sweden, challenge traditional core-periphery dynamics but can exacerbate global inequalities in digital access and resource distribution.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] In the context of digital transformation, data centers enable the expansion of cloud computing, AI, and machine learning, but at significant ecological and social costs.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Critics from science and technology studies (STS) highlight how corporate sustainability pledges, such as carbon neutrality targets by companies like Microsoft and Google, often rely on offsets and renewable subsidies that privatize benefits while causing social and environmental harms.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where data centers' intensive use of public resources (like electricity grids and water supplies) represents an enclosure, with tech firms receiving tax breaks and priority access at the expense of local communities.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Jobs created by data centers tend to be temporary or few in number.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] A study found the productivity increases enabled by data centers are multiple times larger than gross external damages.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Social mobilizations against data centers help shape the discourse around growth of the industry, raise public awareness of issues data centers present, and may impact public policy.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Groups opposed to new data center projects have expressed concern that digital infrastructure exploits local resources 'to the benefit of actors and institutions residing elsewhere'.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] This may occur when data being processed in a facility belongs to actors in other countries, but local people bear the burdens of water and energy use.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] In the U.S., bipartisan community resistance to data center development has grown, with residents voicing concerns about water scarcity, rising utility bills, noise pollution, and urban sprawl.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Facilities in rural areas of the U.S. have been focal points for local resistance.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Data Center Watch reported that multiple projects collectively worth $64 billion had been stopped or delayed between May 2024 and March 2025.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] An additional $98 billion worth of projects were blocked or delayed between March and June 2025.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] A Gallup poll taken in March 2026 reported seven out of ten Americans oppose data center projects in their area.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Outside of the U.S., protests in the Netherlands led to a temporary national ban on new mega-centers in 2022.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] In Chile, protests by activists to protect water reserves led to Google withdrawing plans to build a data center.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] In the United Kingdom, "March Against the Machines" protests were held.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Residents have been concerned about air, water, and noise pollution, as well as property devaluation, traffic, and the risk of fires.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Other environmental concerns involving AI data centers include e-waste and the embodied energy of construction materials, such as concrete and cement.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] data center, they would orbit above the dawn / dusk transition of the planet.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Housing data centers in space has been proposed for low Earth orbit (LEO).
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] The theoretical advantages are that of space-based solar power, in addition to aiding in weather forecasting and weather prediction computation from weather satellites, and the ability to freely scale up.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] However, it is difficult to design cooling systems in space, as convection is not available and sunlight causes large temperature fluctuations.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] Other challenges include damage from cosmic rays and micrometeorites.
[src:linode-akamai/data-center-p02] The design and shape of data centers could change rapidly in the not-too-distant future with the advent of new technologies, such as quantum computing, biocomputation, and synthetic DNA data storage, as examples.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] From the time of its launch in 2003, Linode provided virtual private server (VPS) hosting.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] Linode was acquired by Akamai Technologies in February 2022 for $900 million.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] Linode (a portmanteau of the words Linux and node) was founded in 2003 by Christopher Aker.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] Aker is a graduate of Full Sail University in Florida.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] The company moved its headquarters to Galloway, New Jersey in 2008.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] Linode relocated to the historic Corn Exchange National Bank building in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania in 2018.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] On February 15, 2022, Akamai Technologies announced its intent to acquire Linode for $900 million.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] Akamai's founder and CEO Tom Leighton stated that it sought to "combine Linode's developer-friendly cloud computing capabilities with Akamai’s market-leading edge platform and security services".
[src:linode-akamai/linode] As of November 2019, Linode provided several kinds of virtualization-based computing services with options to meet specific customer needs, such as high memory requirements, dedicated CPU resources, virtual machines with direct access to GPUs.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] Linode provided services in network-based storage and backup servers.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] In September 2013, Linode launched Longview, a system performance monitoring package for Linux that allows users to view performance metrics of their instances from the Linode Cloud Manager.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] In late October 2019, Linode launched its S3-Compatible Object Storage service to enable customers to store large, unstructured data.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] On November 11, 2019, at CNCF KubeCon, Linode announced the availability of its managed Kubernetes engine service.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] In 2012, the accounts of eight Linode customers were compromised, stealing roughly 40,000 bitcoins.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] In 2013, hacking group Hack The Planet (HTP) accessed Linode's web servers by exploiting a technical vulnerability in Adobe's ColdFusion application server.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] Linode said that HTP could not decrypt any financially sensitive information and reset all account passwords.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] Linode announced plans to introduce two-factor authentication for its services in May 2013.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] Starting Christmas Day 2015 and continuing until January 10, 2016, Linode was hit by large and frequent DDoS attacks, which were being caused by a "bad actor" purchasing large amounts of botnet capacity in an attempt to significantly damage Linode's business.
[src:linode-akamai/linode] Linode was the victim of another severe DDoS attack over the 2016 Labor Day weekend.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] A **solid-state drive** (**SSD**) is a type of solid-state storage device that uses integrated circuits to store data persistently.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] It is sometimes called **semiconductor storage device**, **solid-state device**, or **solid-state disk**.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Etymologically, "solid-state drive" partly refers to existing data storage devices like tape drives and hard disk drives, which all used a mechanically driven storage medium.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSDs rely on non-volatile memory, typically NAND flash, to store data in memory cells.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The performance and endurance of SSDs vary depending on the number of bits stored per cell, ranging from high-performing single-level cells (SLC) to more affordable but slower quad-level cells (QLC).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In addition to flash-based SSDs, other technologies such as 3D XPoint offer faster speeds and higher endurance through different data storage mechanisms.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Unlike traditional hard disk drives (HDDs), SSDs have no moving parts, allowing them to deliver faster data access speeds, reduced latency, increased resistance to physical shock, lower power consumption, and silent operation.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Often interfaced to a system in the same way as HDDs, SSDs are used in a variety of devices, including personal computers, enterprise servers, and mobile devices.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] However, SSDs are generally more expensive on a per-gigabyte basis and have a finite number of write cycles, which can lead to data loss over time.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Despite these limitations, SSDs are increasingly replacing HDDs, especially in performance-critical applications and as primary storage in many consumer devices.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSDs come in various form factors and interface types, including SATA, PCIe, and NVMe, each offering different levels of performance.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Hybrid storage solutions, such as solid-state hybrid drives (SSHDs), combine SSD and HDD technologies to offer improved performance at a lower cost than pure SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] An SSD stores data in semiconductor cells, with its properties varying according to the number of bits stored in each cell (between 1 and 4).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Single-level cells (SLC) store one bit of data per cell and provide higher performance and endurance.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In contrast, multi-level cells (MLC), triple-level cells (TLC), and quad-level cells (QLC) store more data per cell but have lower performance and endurance.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSDs using 3D XPoint technology, such as Intel's Optane, store data by changing electrical resistance instead of storing electrical charges in cells, which can provide faster speeds and longer data persistence compared to conventional flash memory.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSDs based on NAND flash slowly leak charge when not powered, while heavily used consumer drives may start losing data typically after one to two years unpowered in storage.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSDs have a limited lifetime number of writes, and also slow down as they reach their full storage capacity.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSDs also have internal parallelism that allows them to manage multiple operations simultaneously, which enhances their performance.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Unlike HDDs and similar electromechanical magnetic storage, SSDs do not have moving mechanical parts, which provides advantages such as resistance to physical shock, quieter operation, and faster access times.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Their lower latency results in higher input/output rates (IOPS) than HDDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Some SSDs are combined with traditional hard drives in hybrid configurations, such as Intel's Hystor and Apple's Fusion Drive.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] These drives use both flash memory and spinning magnetic disks in order to improve the performance of frequently accessed data.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SATA and SAS) and standard HDD form factors allow such SSDs to be used as drop-in replacements for HDDs in computers and other devices.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Newer form factors such as mSATA, M.2, U.2, NF1/M.3/NGFF, XFM Express (*Crossover Flash Memory*, form factor XT2) and EDSFF and higher speed interfaces such as NVM Express (NVMe) over PCI Express (PCIe) can further increase performance over HDD performance.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Traditional HDD benchmarks tend to focus on the performance characteristics such as rotational latency and seek time.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] As SSDs do not need to spin or seek to locate data, they are vastly superior to HDDs in such tests.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] However, SSDs have challenges with mixed reads and writes, and their performance may degrade over time.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Therefore, SSD testing typically looks at when the full drive is first used, as the new and empty drive may have much better write performance than it would show after only weeks of use.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The reliability of both HDDs and SSDs varies greatly among models.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Some field failure rates indicate that SSDs are significantly more reliable than HDDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] However, SSDs are sensitive to sudden power interruption, sometimes resulting in aborted writes or even cases of the complete loss of the drive.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Most of the advantages of solid-state drives over traditional hard drives are due to their ability to access data completely electronically instead of electromechanically, resulting in superior transfer speeds and mechanical ruggedness.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] On the other hand, hard disk drives offer significantly higher capacity for their price.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In traditional HDDs, a rewritten file will generally occupy the same location on the disk surface as the original file, whereas in SSDs the new copy will often be written to different NAND cells for the purpose of wear leveling.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The wear-leveling algorithms are complex and difficult to test exhaustively.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] As a result, one major cause of data loss in SSDs is firmware bugs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] While both memory cards and most SSDs use flash memory, they have very different characteristics, including power consumption, performance, size, and reliability.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Originally, solid state drives were shaped and mounted in the computer like hard drives.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In contrast, memory cards (such as Secure Digital (SD), CompactFlash (CF), and many others) were originally designed for digital cameras and later found their way into cell phones, gaming devices, GPS units, etc.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Most memory cards are physically smaller than SSDs, and designed to be inserted and removed repeatedly.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSDs have different failure modes from traditional magnetic hard drives.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Because solid-state drives contain no moving parts, they are generally not subject to mechanical failures.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] However, other types of failures can occur.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For example, incomplete or failed writes due to sudden power loss may be more problematic than with HDDs, and the failure of a single chip may result in the loss of all data stored on it.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Nonetheless, studies indicate that SSDs are generally reliable, often exceeding their manufacturer-stated lifespan and have lower failure rates than HDDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] However, studies also note that SSDs experience higher rates of uncorrectable errors, which can lead to data loss, compared to HDDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The basic parameter for determining the lifespan of Flash-NAND systems is the number of programming-erase (P/E) cycles.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The TBW parameter is the product of the P/E cycle resource and the SSD capacity.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For an SSD with a capacity of 1 TB and TBW = 600 TB, the number of P/E cycles is 600.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Recovering data from SSDs presents challenges due to the non-linear and complex nature of data storage in solid-state drives.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The internal operations of SSDs vary by manufacturer, with commands (e.g.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] TRIM and the ATA Secure Erase) and programs (e.g. hdparm) being able to erase and modify the bits of a deleted file.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In a distributed computing environment, SSDs can be used as a distributed cache layer that temporarily absorbs the large volume of user requests to slower HDD-based backend storage systems.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This layer provides much higher bandwidth and lower latency than the storage system would, and can be managed in a number of forms, such as a distributed key-value database and a distributed file system.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] On supercomputers, this layer is typically referred to as burst buffer.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Flash-based solid-state drives can be used to create network appliances from general-purpose personal computer hardware.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] A write protected flash drive containing the operating system and application software can substitute for larger, less reliable disk drives or CD-ROMs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Appliances built this way can provide an inexpensive alternative to expensive router and firewall hardware.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSDs based on an SD card with a live SD operating system are easily write-locked.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Combined with a cloud computing environment or other writable medium, an OS booted from a write-locked SD card is reliable, persistent and impervious to permanent corruption.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In 2011, Intel introduced a caching mechanism for their Z68 chipset (and mobile derivatives) called Smart Response Technology, which allows a SATA SSD to be used as a cache (configurable as write-through or write-back) for a conventional, magnetic hard disk drive.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] A similar technology is available on HighPoint's RocketHybrid PCIe card.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Solid-state hybrid drives (SSHDs) are based on the same principle, but integrate some amount of flash memory on board of a conventional drive instead of using a separate SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The flash layer in these drives can be accessed independently from the magnetic storage by the host using ATA-8 commands, allowing the operating system to manage it.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For example, Microsoft's ReadyDrive technology explicitly stores portions of the hibernation file in the cache of these drives when the system hibernates, making the subsequent resume faster.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Dual-drive hybrid systems are combining the usage of separate SSD and HDD devices installed in the same computer, with overall performance optimization managed by the computer user, or by the computer's operating system software.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Examples of this type of system are bcache and dm-cache on Linux, and Apple's Fusion Drive.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The primary components of an SSD are the controller and the memory used to store data.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Traditionally, early SSDs used volatile DRAM for storage, but since 2009, most SSDs utilize non-volatile NAND flash memory, which retains data even when powered off.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Flash memory SSDs store data in metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) integrated circuit chips, using non-volatile floating-gate memory cells.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Every SSD includes a controller, which manages the data flow between the NAND memory and the host computer.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The controller is an embedded processor that runs firmware to optimize performance, managing data, and ensuring data integrity.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The overall performance of an SSD can scale with the number of parallel NAND chips and the efficiency of the controller.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For example, controllers that enable parallel processing of NAND flash chips can improve bandwidth and reduce latency.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The number of flash memory channel increases, the delay of raw flash memory (such as ONFI based NAND flash) decreases, and the bandwidth of raw flash memory increases.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Micron and Intel pioneered faster SSDs by implementing techniques such as data striping and interleaving to enhance read/write speeds.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] More recently, SandForce introduced controllers that incorporate data compression to reduce the amount of data written to the flash memory, potentially increasing both performance and endurance.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Wear leveling is a technique used in SSDs to ensure that write and erase operations are distributed evenly across all blocks of the flash memory.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Without this, specific blocks could wear out prematurely due to repeated use, reducing the overall lifespan of the SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The process moves data that is infrequently changed (cold data) from heavily used blocks, so that data that changes more frequently (hot data) can be written to those blocks.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This helps distribute wear more evenly across the entire SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] However, this process introduces additional writes, known as write amplification, which must be managed to balance performance and durability.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Most SSDs use non-volatile NAND flash memory for data storage, primarily due to its cost-effectiveness and ability to retain data without a constant power supply.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] NAND flash-based SSDs store data in semiconductor cells, with the specific architecture influencing performance, endurance, and cost.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Over time, SSD controllers have improved the efficiency of NAND flash, incorporating techniques such as interleaved memory, advanced error correction, and wear leveling to optimize performance and extend the lifespan of the drive.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Lower-end SSDs often use QLC or TLC memory, while higher-end drives for enterprise or performance-critical applications may use MLC or SLC.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In addition to the flat (planar) NAND structure, many SSDs now use 3D NAND (or V-NAND), where memory cells are stacked vertically, increasing storage density while improving performance and reducing costs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Some SSDs use volatile DRAM instead of NAND flash, offering very high-speed data access but requiring a constant power supply to retain data.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] DRAM-based SSDs are typically used in specialized applications where performance is prioritized over cost or non-volatility.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Many SSDs, such as NVDIMM devices, are equipped with backup power sources such as internal batteries or external AC/DC adapters.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] These power sources ensure data is transferred to a backup system (usually NAND flash or another storage medium) in the event of power loss, preventing data corruption or loss.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Similarly, ULLtraDIMM devices use components designed for DIMM modules, but only use flash memory, similar to a DRAM SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] DRAM-based SSDs are often used for tasks where data must be accessed at high speeds with low latency, such as in high-performance computing or certain server environments.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] 3D XPoint is a type of non-volatile memory technology developed by Intel and Micron, announced in 2015.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] It operates by changing the electrical resistance of materials in its cells, offering much faster access times than NAND flash.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] 3D XPoint-based SSDs, such as Intel's Optane drives, provide lower latency and higher endurance than NAND-based drives, although they are more expensive per gigabyte.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Drives known as hybrid drives or solid-state hybrid drives (SSHDs) use a hybrid of spinning disks and flash memory.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Some SSDs use magnetoresistive random-access memory (MRAM) for storing data.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Many flash-based SSDs include a small amount of volatile DRAM as a cache, similar to the buffers in hard disk drives.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This cache can temporarily hold data while it is being written to the flash memory, and it also stores metadata such as the mapping of logical blocks to physical locations on the SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This cache may also temporarily hold data while it being recently read from the flash memory.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Some SSD controllers, like those from SandForce, achieve high performance without using an external DRAM cache.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] These designs rely on other mechanisms, such as on-chip SRAM, to manage data and minimize power consumption.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Additionally, some SSDs use an SLC buffer mechanism to temporarily store data in single-level cell (SLC) mode, even on multi-level cell (MLC) or triple-level cell (TLC) SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This improves write performance by allowing data to be written to faster SLC storage before being moved to slower, higher-capacity MLC or TLC storage.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] On NVMe SSDs, Host Memory Buffer (HMB) technology allows the SSD to use a portion of the system's DRAM instead of relying on a built-in DRAM cache, reducing costs while maintaining a high level of performance.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In certain high-end consumer and enterprise SSDs, larger amounts of DRAM are included to cache both file table mappings and written data, reducing write amplification and enhances overall performance.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Higher-performing SSDs may include capacitors, supercapacitors or batteries, which helps preserve data integrity in the event of an unexpected power loss.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The capacitor or battery provides enough power to allow the data in the cache to be written to the non-volatile memory, ensuring no data is lost.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In some SSDs that use multi-level cell (MLC) flash memory, a potential issue known as "lower page corruption" can occur if power is lost while programming an upper page.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This can result in previously written data becoming corrupted.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] To address this, some high-end SSDs incorporate supercapacitors to ensure all data can be safely written during a sudden power loss.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Some consumer SSDs have built-in capacitors to save critical data such as the Flash Translation Layer (FTL) mapping table.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Examples include the Crucial M500 and Intel 320 series.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Enterprise-class SSDs, such as the Intel DC S3700 series, often come with more robust power-loss protection mechanisms like supercapacitors or batteries.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The host interface of an SSD refers to the physical connector and the signaling methods used to communicate between the SSD and the host system.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This interface is managed by the SSD's controller and is often similar to those found in traditional hard disk drives (HDDs).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSDs may support various logical interfaces, which define the command sets used by operating systems to communicate with the SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The size and shape of any device are largely driven by the size and shape of the components used to make that device.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Traditional HDDs and optical drives are designed around the rotating platter(s) or optical disc along with the spindle motor inside.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Since an SSD is made up of various interconnected integrated circuits (ICs) and an interface connector, its shape is no longer limited to the shape of rotating media drives.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The lack of moving parts and light weight meant that an SSD can have no shell and simply appear in the shape of a plug-in board.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] On the other end of the size spectrum, some solid-state storage solutions come in a larger chassis that may even be a rack-mount form factor with numerous SSDs inside.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] They would all connect to a common bus inside the chassis and connect outside the box with a single connector.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For general computer use, the 2.5-inch form factor (typically found in laptops and used for most SATA SSDs) was the most popular in the 2010s, in three thicknesses (7.0mm, 9.5mm, 14.8 or 15.0mm; with 12.0mm also available for some models).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For desktop computers with 3.5-inch hard disk drive slots, a simple adapter plate can be used to make such a drive fit.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Other types of form factors are more common in enterprise applications.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] An SSD can also be completely integrated in the other circuitry of the device, as in the Apple MacBook Air (starting with the fall 2010 model).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] As of 2014, mSATA and M.2 form factors also gained popularity, primarily in laptops.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The benefit of using a current HDD form factor would be to take advantage of the extensive infrastructure already in place to mount and connect the drives to the host system.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] These traditional form factors are known by the size of the rotating media (i.e., 5.25-inch, 3.5-inch, 2.5-inch or 1.8-inch) and not the dimensions of the drive casing.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] A *disk-on-a-module* (*DOM*) is a flash drive with either 40/44-pin Parallel ATA (PATA) or SATA interface, intended to be plugged directly into the motherboard and used as a computer hard disk drive (HDD).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] DOM devices emulate a traditional hard disk drive, resulting in no need for special drivers or other specific operating system support.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] DOMs are usually used in embedded systems, which are often deployed in harsh environments where mechanical HDDs would simply fail, or in thin clients because of small size, low power consumption, and silent operation.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The most traditional emulates the standard interface, with the 7-pin SATA data connector placed beside the 15-pin SATA power connector.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] An example is the "half-slim SATA" MO-297 size standard.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] To save board space, smaller SATA DOMs were made that only use the SATA data connector.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Supermicro, relied on a separate Berg connector to deliver power.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] A second type of 2012, made by Innodisk, repurposes the 7th pin of the connector from GND to VCC (+5V).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] A third type called "pin 8 power" replaces the two plastic structural elements on the sides with two metal contacts for GND and VCC.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] These new types of SATADOMs are now so popular that the older 7+15-pin type is virtually not considered to be "SATADOMs" any more, especially as few motherboards provide such an interface.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] There are also USB DOMs designed to be plugging into the USB 2.0 header pins on a motherboard.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] As of 2016, DOM storage capacities range from 4 MB to 128 GB with different variations in physical layouts, including vertical or horizontal orientation.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For applications where space is at a premium, like for ultrabooks or tablet computers, a few compact form factors were standardized for flash-based SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] There is the mSATA form factor, which uses the PCI Express Mini Card physical layout.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] It remains electrically compatible with the PCI Express Mini Card interface specification while requiring an additional connection to the SATA host controller through the same connector.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] A higher-performance SSD may use the Mini-PCIe to access the PCIe bus directly.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] M.2 form factor, formerly known as the Next Generation Form Factor (NGFF), is a natural transition from the mSATA and physical layout it used, to a more usable and more advanced form factor.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] While mSATA took advantage of an existing form factor and connector, M.2 has been designed to maximize usage of the card space, while minimizing the footprint.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The M.2 standard allows both SATA and PCI Express SSDs to be fitted onto M.2 modules.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Before M.2 was standardized, one of the main ways to access the PCIe bus for faster-than-SATA/SAS speed on a server was through the PCIe slot.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] A common shape is called HHHL (Half Height Half Length), or AIC (Add in Card) SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Some primitive PCIe SSDs do not access the PCIe bus directly, but simply had a PCIe-to-SATA/SAS bridge device and a number of SATA or SAS flash controllers attached.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This was considered acceptable in 2010, when true PCIe SSDs were still new.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This shape remains in use for some high performance, high capacity drives.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The PCIe slot offers 16 lanes of data and 75 watts of power, still much larger than what a M.2 slot can provide.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] It also provides space for a large heat sink.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] There are also adapter boards that converts other form factors, especially M.2 drives with PCIe interface, into regular add-in cards.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In the early 2000s, a few companies introduced SSDs in Ball Grid Array (BGA) form factors, such as M-Systems' (now SanDisk) DiskOnChip and Silicon Storage Technology's NANDrive (now produced by Greenliant Systems), and Memoright's M1000 for use in embedded systems.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The main benefits of BGA SSDs are their low power consumption, small chip package size to fit into compact subsystems, and that they can be soldered directly onto a system motherboard to reduce adverse effects from vibration and shock.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Such embedded drives now often adhere to the eMMC and eUFS standards.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Many of the DRAM-based solutions in 2014 use a box that is often designed to fit in a rack-mount system.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The number of DRAM components required to get sufficient capacity to store the data along with the backup power supplies requires a larger space than traditional HDD form factors.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The flexibility of the SSD also allows for many unusual form factors, some of which had been important in its early adoption in PCs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For example, the SATADIMM from Viking Technology uses an empty DDR3 DIMM slot on the motherboard to provide power to the SSD with a separate SATA connector to provide the data connection back to the computer.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The result is an easy-to-install SSD with a capacity equal to drives that typically take a full 2.5-inch drive bay.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The first devices resembling solid-state drives (SSDs) used semiconductor technology, with an early example being the 1978 StorageTek STC 4305.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This device was a plug-compatible replacement for the IBM 2305 hard drive, initially using charge-coupled devices for storage and later switching to dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The STC 4305 was significantly faster than its mechanical counterparts and cost around $400,000 for a 45 MB capacity.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Though early SSD-like devices existed, they were not widely used due to their high cost and small storage capacity.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In the late 1980s, companies like Zitel began selling DRAM-based SSD products under the name "RAMDisk." These devices were primarily used in specialized systems like those made by UNIVAC and Perkin-Elmer.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Top and bottom sides of a 100GB Intel DC S3700 SATA SSD and a 120GB Intel 535 mSATA SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Flash memory, a key component in modern SSDs, was invented in 1980 by Fujio Masuoka at Toshiba.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Flash-based SSDs were patented in 1989 by the founders of SanDisk, which released its first product in 1991: a 20 MB SSD for IBM laptops.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] While the storage capacity was limited and the price high (around $1,000), this marked the beginning of a transition to flash memory as an alternative to traditional hard drives.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In the 1990s, new manufacturers of flash memory drives emerged, including STEC, Inc., M-Systems, and BiTMICRO.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] As the technology advanced, SSDs saw dramatic improvements in capacity, speed, and affordability.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] By 2016, commercially available SSDs had more capacity than the largest available HDDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] By 2018, flash-based SSDs had reached capacities of up to 100 TB in enterprise products, with consumer SSDs offering up to 16 TB.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] These advancements were accompanied by significant increases in read and write speeds, with some high-end consumer models reaching speeds of up to 14.5 GB/s.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In 2021, NVMe 2.0 with Zoned Namespaces (ZNS) was announced.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] ZNS allows data to be mapped directly to its physical location in memory, providing direct access on an SSD without a flash translation layer.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In 2024, Samsung announced what it called the world's first SSD with a hybrid PCIe interface, the Samsung 990 EVO.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The hybrid interface runs in either the x4 PCIe 4.0 or x2 PCIe 5.0 modes, a first for an M.2 SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSD prices have also fallen dramatically, with the cost per gigabyte decreasing from around $50,000 in 1991 to less than $0.05 by 2020.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Enterprise flash drives (EFDs) are designed for high-performance applications requiring fast input/output operations per second (IOPS), reliability, and energy efficiency.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] EFDs often have higher specifications than consumer SSDs, making them suitable for mission-critical applications.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The term was first used by EMC in 2008 to describe SSDs built for enterprise environments.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] One example of an EFD is the Intel DC S3700 series, launched in 2012.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] These drives were notable for their consistent performance, maintaining IOPS variation within a narrow range, which is crucial for enterprise environments.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Another significant product is the Toshiba PX02SS series, launched in 2016.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Designed for write-intensive applications like online transaction processing, these drives achieved impressive read and write speeds and high endurance ratings.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In 2017, Intel introduced SSDs based on 3D XPoint technology under the Optane brand.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Unlike NAND flash, 3D XPoint uses a different method to store data, offering higher IOPS performance, although sequential read and write speeds remain slower compared to traditional SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] As SSD technology continues to improve, they are increasingly used in ultra-mobile PCs and lightweight laptop systems.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The first flash-memory SSD based PC to become available was the Sony Vaio UX90, announced for pre-order on 27 June 2006 and began shipping in Japan on 3 July 2006 with a 16 GB flash memory hard drive.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Another of the first mainstream releases of SSD was the XO Laptop, built as part of the One Laptop Per Child project.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Mass production of these computers, built for children in developing countries, began in December 2007.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] By 2009, Dell, Toshiba, Asus, Apple, and Lenovo had begun producing laptops with SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] By 2010, Apple's MacBook Air line began using solid state drives as the default.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In 2011, Intel's Ultrabook became the first widely available consumer computers using SSDs aside from the MacBook Air.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] At present, SSD devices are widely used and distributed by a number of companies, with a small number of companies manufacturing the NAND flash devices within them.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] SSD shipments were approximately 11 million units in 2009, rising to 17.3 million units in 2011 for a total market value of US$5 billion.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Shipments continued to grow to 39 million units in 2012 and were projected to reach 83 million units in 2013, 201.4 million units in 2016, and 227 million units in 2017.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The global solid-state drive (SSD) market is projected to grow significantly between 2024 and 2030, driven by rising demand for data center expansion, cloud computing services, and consumer electronics upgrades.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In a 2024 report, Grand View Research estimated the SSD market at USD 19.1 billion in 2023 and projected it to reach USD 55.1 billion by 2030.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In a separate 2024 study, Mordor Intelligence valued the market at USD 63.45 billion for 2024, forecasting growth to USD 172.82 billion by 2030.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The same file systems used on hard disk drives can typically also be used on solid state drives.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] File systems that support SSDs generally also support the TRIM command, which helps the SSD to recycle discarded data.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The file system does not need to manage wear leveling or other flash memory characteristics, as they are handled internally by the SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] F2FS, JFFS2) help to reduce write amplification on SSDs, especially in situations where only very small amounts of data are changed, such as when updating file-system metadata.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] If an operating system does not support using TRIM on discrete swap partitions, it might be possible to use swap files inside an ordinary file system instead.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For example, macOS does not support swap partitions; it only swaps to files within a file system, so it can use TRIM when, for example, swap files are deleted.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Since 2010, standard Linux drive utilities have taken care of appropriate partition alignment by default.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Kernel support for the TRIM operation was introduced in version 2.6.33 of the Linux kernel mainline, released on 24 February 2010.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The ext4, Btrfs, XFS, JFS, and F2FS file systems include support for the discard (TRIM or UNMAP) function.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Non-native file systems such as exFAT and NTFS-3G also support TRIM.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] To automatically make use of TRIM on file deletion, a file system must be mounted using the `discard` parameter.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Linux swap partitions are by default performing discard operations when the underlying drive supports TRIM, with the possibility to turn them off.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Support for queued TRIM, a SATA 3.1 feature that results in TRIM commands not disrupting the command queues, was introduced in Linux kernel 3.12, released on November 2, 2013.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] An alternative to the kernel-level TRIM operation is to use a user-space utility called fstrim that goes through all of the unused blocks in a filesystem and dispatches TRIM commands for those areas.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Thefstrimutility is usually run by cron or systemd as a scheduled task.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] A filesystem that supports TRIM remains required.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Whether formatting or resizing trims the unused space depends on the implementation.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For example, the mke2fs program for formatting ext2/3/4 defaults to issuing a TRIM command (if supported) to the entire block, but the resize2fs program for resizing ext2/3/4 does not TRIM the space left unused after shrinking.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] TRIM-after-resize is instead done by fdisk or sfdisk, programs that edit the partition table.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] In addition, bcache is designed to have an SSD act as a read/write cache for a slower drive such as an HDD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Versions since Mac OS X 10.6.8 (Snow Leopard) support TRIM but only when used with an Apple-purchased SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] TRIM is not automatically enabled for third-party drives, except for external removable SSDs, although it can be enabled by using third-party utilities such as *Trim Enabler*.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The status of TRIM can be checked in the System Information application or in the `system_profiler` command-line tool.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Versions since OS X 10.10.4 (Yosemite) include `sudo trimforce enable` as a Terminal command that enables TRIM on non-Apple SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] There is also a technique to enable TRIM in versions earlier than Mac OS X 10.6.8, although it remains uncertain whether TRIM is actually utilized properly in those cases.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Prior to Windows 7, Microsoft Windows did not take any specific measures to support solid state drives.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] From Windows 7, the standard NTFS file system provides support for the TRIM command.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] By default, Windows 7 and newer versions execute TRIM commands automatically if the device is detected to be a solid-state drive *and* the filesystem driver supports TRIM (NTFS or ReFS).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] However, because TRIM irreversibly resets all freed space, it may be desirable to disable support where enabling data recovery is preferred over wear leveling.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Windows implements TRIM for more than just file-delete operations.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The TRIM operation is integrated with partition- and volume-level commands such as *format* and *delete*, with file-system commands relating to truncate and compression, and with the System Restore (also known as Volume Snapshot) feature.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The SuperFetch feature will also not materially improve performance and causes additional overhead in the system and SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Since Windows 8.1, the Windows Defrag routine would instead "retrim" (TRIM) partitions detected as SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Windows Vista generally expects hard disk drives rather than SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Windows Vista includes ReadyBoost to exploit characteristics of USB-connected flash devices, but for SSDs it only improves the default partition alignment to prevent read-modify-write operations that reduce the speed of SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Most SSDs are typically split into 4 KiB sectors, while earlier systems may be based on 512 byte sectors with their default partition setups unaligned to the 4 KiB boundaries.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Windows Vista does not send the TRIM command to solid-state drives, but some third-party utilities such as SSD Doctor will periodically scan the drive and TRIM the appropriate entries.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Windows 7 and later versions have native support for SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The operating system detects the presence of an SSD and optimizes operation accordingly.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For SSD devices, Windows 7 disables ReadyBoost and automatic defragmentation.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Despite the initial statement by Steven Sinofsky before the release of Windows 7, however, defragmentation is not disabled, even though its behavior on SSDs differs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] One reason is the low performance of Volume Shadow Copy Service on fragmented SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The second reason is to avoid reaching the practical maximum number of file fragments that a volume can handle.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Windows 7 also includes support for the TRIM command to reduce garbage collection for data that the operating system has already determined is no longer valid.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Windows 8.1 and later Windows systems also support automatic TRIM for PCI Express SSDs based on NVMe.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] For Windows 7, the KB2990941 update is required for this functionality and needs to be integrated into Windows Setup using DISM if Windows 7 has to be installed on the NVMe SSD.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Windows 8/8.1 also supports the SCSI unmap command, an analog of SATA TRIM, for USB-attached SSDs or SATA-to-USB enclosures.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] It is also supported over USB Attached SCSI Protocol (UASP).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] While Windows 7 supported automatic TRIM for internal SATA SSDs, Windows 8.1 and above support manual TRIM as well as automatic TRIM for SATA, NVMe and USB-attached SSDs.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Manual TRIM is accessed through the expanded Windows Defrag utility.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] Solaris as of version 10 Update 6 (released in October 2008), and recent versions of OpenSolaris, Solaris Express Community Edition, Illumos, Linux with ZFS on Linux, and FreeBSD all can use SSDs as a performance booster for ZFS.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] A low-latency SSD can be used for the ZFS Intent Log (ZIL), where it is named the SLOG.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] An SSD may also be used for the level 2 Adaptive Replacement Cache (L2ARC), which is used to cache data for reading.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] ZFS for FreeBSD introduced support for TRIM on September 23, 2012.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The Unix File System also supports the TRIM command.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The following are noted standardization organizations and bodies that work to create standards for solid-state drives (and other computer storage devices).
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] The table below also includes organizations which promote the use of solid-state drives.
[src:linode-akamai/solid-state-drive] This is not necessarily an exhaustive list.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] A **virtual private server** (**VPS**) or **virtual dedicated server** (**VDS**) is a virtual machine sold as a service by an Internet hosting company.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] A virtual private server runs its own copy of an operating system (OS), and customers may have superuser-level access to that operating system instance, so they can install almost any software that runs on that OS.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] For many purposes, it is functionally equivalent to a dedicated physical server and, being software-defined, can be created and configured more easily.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] A virtual server costs less than an equivalent physical server.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] However, as virtual servers share the underlying physical hardware with other VPS, performance may be lower depending on the workload of any other executing virtual machines.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] The force driving server virtualization is similar to that which led to the development of time-sharing and multiprogramming in the past.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] Partitioning a single server to appear as multiple servers has been increasingly common on microcomputers since the release of VMware ESX Server in 2001.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] VMware later replaced ESX Server with VMware ESXi, a more lightweight hypervisor architecture that eliminated the Linux-based Console Operating System (COS) used in the original ESX.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] The physical server typically runs a hypervisor which is tasked with creating, releasing, and managing the resources of "guest" operating systems, or virtual machines.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] These guest operating systems are allocated a share of resources of the physical server, typically in a manner in which the guest is not aware of any other physical resources except for those allocated to it by the hypervisor.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] There are several approaches to virtualization.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] In hardware virtualization, a hypervisor such as the Kernel-based Virtual Machine allows each virtual machine (VM) to run its own independent kernel, providing greater isolation from the host system.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] By contrast, container-based virtualization—for example OpenVZ—shares the host kernel among multiple containers.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] This can improve resource efficiency, but usually offers less isolation and fewer customization options for each instance.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] Many companies offer virtual private server hosting or virtual dedicated server hosting as an extension for web hosting services.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] There are several challenges to consider when licensing proprietary software in multi-tenant virtual environments.
[src:linode-akamai/virtual-private-server] With *unmanaged* or *self-managed* hosting, the customer is left to administer their own server instance.
